* IP --> the truck that have the boxes (UDP , TCP) that hold my data to transfer it across road"networkEt"(Ethernet , Fiber , DSL)
* Ethernet , Fiber , DSL --> physical layer || Ethernet: Directly connected by Copper cables between your Device and the Switch/Router. 
* DSL (Digital Subscriber Line): Directly connected between the Central Office (CO) and your Home Router using telephone copper lines.
* Fiber / Coaxial: High-speed physical paths that connect the ISP (Internet Service Provider) to your building or neighborhood. (better version of DSL)
* IP --> network layer
* TCP , UDP --> transport layer
* Data Encapsulation :
Ethernet Frame (Layer 2):
Header: Contains the MAC Address (Source & Destination).
Payload: Carries the entire IP Packet.
Note: MAC Address is a fixed physical code (Hexadecimal) burned into the NIC.
IP Packet (Layer 3):
Header: Contains the IP Address (Source & Destination).
Payload: Carries the entire TCP Segment.
Note: IP Address is a logical address that changes when you change networks.
TCP Segment (Layer 4):
Header: Contains the Port Number.
Payload: Carries the HTTP Data.
Note: Port Number identifies the specific application (e.g., Port 80 for Browser).
Application Data (Layer 7):
Content: The actual HTTP Data.
Note: This is the real content (image, text, or file) being sent.
* TCP (transmission control protocol) --> make sure that the data sent successfully if something failed stop until
resent successfully (recovery from error) (TCP data > , < TCP ack "three-way handshake") , flow control if the sending speed more than recieving speed it can manage how much 
data should be sent (windowing) to prevent (buffer overflow) , TCP needs IP adress first to send the data
* UDP (user datagram protocol) --> connectionless (Doesn't establish a "handshake" before sending data. It just starts sending),
unreliable (no error recovery) , if the data failed to be sent it will be skipped no flow control ,
cannot be cancelled (doesn't stop to retransmission) 
* protocols that uses UDP :
1- DHCP (dynamic host configuration protocol) --> Used to automatically assign IP addresses.
Why UDP? Because a device doesn't have an IP address yet to start a TCP connection, so it must Broadcast via UDP.
Reliability: The DHCP Application Layer ensures the IP is assigned successfully using DORA steps:
Discover: Device searches for a server (Broadcast).
Offer: Server shows an available IP.
Request: Device accepts the IP address.
Acknowledgment: Server confirmation (Finalizes the lease).
2- TFTP (trivial file system protocol) --> a simple version of FTP used for quick file transfers 
(like booting a diskless workstation) without the complexity of TCP.
